ent U.S. trade policies are harmful or helpful, but they all agree that there is a new trend toward focusing on results-oriented policies in specific markets and with particular trading partners. These twelve essays by leading international economists explore crucial issues in U.S. trade policy today. Topics examined include the markets for automobile and automobile parts in the United States and Japan, the U.S. response to "unfair" trading practices such as dumping, and the effects of industry- and country-specific policies. Examples include high-technology and agricultural industries and off-shore assembly in U.S. border cities. The volume concludes that some policies can act to both protect imports and promote exports, that the threat of protectionist policies can often have effects that are as pronounced as their implementation, and that regulatory policy has as great an impact on trade and investment patterns as does trade policy itself. It will be of crucial interest to international trade economists, policy specialists, and political scientists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aBusiness. 0aForeign trade promotion. 0aFree trade. 0aInvestments, American. 0aInvestments, Foreign. 0aProtectionism. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aFeenstra, Robert C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226239538423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226239538.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles